preview_comments.text: @ctrl.alt.rees unusual to see in such old tech. Especially considering how easy most of the 70's stuff is to take apart.

@my.retro.tech Yes, they were a bit of a surprise to say the least! Unfortunately someone has already had a go at them with a pair of pliers or something and scratched up the plastic. Good thing is they're inside the battery compartment so it's not like they're visible.

caption.text:
Inside the Pong machine! I was very pleasantly surprised at how clean this thing was inside. Not only that, but I managed to find a way to remove the weird security screws without damaging them. It seems like someone else wasn't so careful at some point in the past which is a bit of a shame.

Oh, and regular viewers will be pleased to see that all of the battery mess cleaned up nicely too! Definitely on to a winner with this one.

Today im gonna share a little secret with you guys as a DM and GM: I improvice my games up to 80%. I genuinly cant have a book in front of me and run that word for word, page after page.. it makes me as a GM hindered and limited. What I usually do is have a mind map of plotpoints, names, puzzles and you name it, then the narrative will come naturally!

One thing I love is rewarding role-playing and problem solving with my players. Let us say that our warlock is out of spells, he only has a staff, a ritual dagger and a half decent dexterity/agility. Worst case, he keeps hitting the enemy, let's say an owlbear with his stick dealing no damage and only makes the beast angry. Instead he jumps up on to the back of the beast and slits the throat with the dagger. If a player does this, I will se it as a cool way to kill a enemy when nothing else works, and allow it with some not so important dice checks.

However, the rules would not allow it, they would say that the warlock used a "improvised weapon" and it deals almost less damage then the staff. In this case I can't care for the rulebook.

And that's also something that many Beginner DM does wrong: the books are guidelines, nothing more nothing less. You will still have an awesome time even if you don't follow the book in every sentence. In all honesty, a good DM knows the rules, but bends them into his players games becouse that's the second most important thing: It's NOT your game, it's the players game you narrate! If your players have a good time, you will have a great time as a DM. The third most important thing is this: Never, I repeat NEVER say "No" to a player. Always try to implement the ideas they have and do as they want even if it might derail the campaign in total chaos, it's your job as a DM to take them on an adventure, and they can always go back to the rails again.

1: books are guidelines, not set in stone.
2: It's the player's game, not the DM's.
3: never, ever say "No" to a player.

If you know these 3 fundamental rules, you have mastered the beginning of becoming a Dungeon Master!

Ghost Recon Breakpoint is hitting our store tomorrow with the release of Gold and Ultimate Editions!

Get it 3 days before Breakpoints general release on Friday 4th October by coming in and loading up with one of these fantastic versions.

Both include the Year 1 pass which offers up 12 months of amazing gameplay!

Why not try Ghost Recon Wildlands whilst you're at it. A tactical and stealth filled game which relies on your strong team work skills and precision shooting to take out pesky cartel members! Get Wildlands for just £19.99 new or £12.99 pre-owned!

Crikey! That whippersnapper has erected a squirrel launcher yonder.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
I was so excited to get •Feudum• to the table despite the supposed awkwardness of the rules and expectations were sky high. We ended up having a total blast! The game is huge in scope and just sucks you into this crazy world of knights and farmers and friars and monsters and contraptions and nourishing your followers with wine (the alternative is eating squirrels). And it looks absolutely amazing on the table. We are playing again this coming weekend, and many more weekends I suspect. About the rules I must say that the ”weight” is exaggerated. It’s by no means a gateway game even though the artistic style is one of ”a jolly game”. But if you’ve played games like Star Wars Rebellion, Gmt’s Coin, Through the Ages or the like.... •Feudum• isnt as ”weighty” as any of those. Expect more updates this coming weekend.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

D&D Night: “For what I have in mind, the lubricant is going to have to glow in the dark and kill sharks.” Our heroes set out on the waterways and didn’t just find some great white sharks, but instead found the greatest white sharks. Sharks are nature’s way of seasoning the water with unmitigated fear. Sometimes, after eating you they rejaculate your body just so they can use it as a mannequin in their boutiques of horror. Other times they just masticate your body like it’s some kind of beef jerky meat chewing gum type situation. Fortunately, The Order Of Poor Choices® were able to flee before their innards became outards, in an adventure so epic it makes Jaws: The Revenge look like Jaws 2.

preview_comments.text: So great to see my boy @ixtran make this line up, totally over the moon for him. We started off as cosplayer and photographer and now extremely close friends! Appreciation for all his hard work epic to see 😍😍

caption.text:
MONTHLY REPORT - 5
Here is finally the fifth monthly report. The cosplay archive I would like to create with my page is getting bigger and bigger. The page has passed 200 followers and now has almost reached 300 followers. This month Milan Games Week was held where I met the really nice and talented @atena_cosplay . I took a photo of his beautiful Pizza Delivery Sivir cosplay that I posted in the last few days but I didn't include it among the best cosplay of the month because I think there were better ones than her one even though I really like it very much. Also this month it was very hard to choose the best cosplay of the month. Below are listed the best cosplays of this month that you can also see by swiping to the right of the Monthly Report Image:
- @alex_reismontel as Demonic Vi from League of Legends
- @helenstifler as Neeko from League of Legends
- @ixtran as Fl4k from Borderlands 3
- @holtsclawcosplay as Cayde-6 from Destiny Videogames Series
- @xenon_cosplay as Lady Maria from Bloodborne
- @okoer_cosplay as Project Ebonblade Sylvanas from World of Warcraft - @maul_cosplay as Zane from Borderlands 3
- @ri.care as Mad Moxxi from Borderlands Videogame Series
- @rebeccaseals as The Other Mother from Coraline Movie ▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️ #cosplay #cosplaygirls #cosplaygirlsofinstagram #cosplayers #cosplayofinstagram #cosplaygirl #cosplayer #cosplayofig #cosplayart #cosplayartist #manga #mangacosplay #mangacosplayers #mangacosplays #mangagirls #mangaboys #anime #animecosplay #animecosplays #animecosplayers #videogames #games #gaming #gamers #gamergirls #gamerboys #geek #geekboys #geekgirls
